text: So I remember starting my career, it was about February 2001. And one of the key things, I was trying to think back to what was work like at that time. And we were all wearing full on suits, first of all, jackets, ties, the whole lot. And we were doing research. I spent all day in front of a computer in the office. And then you go back home. And nowadays, of course, mostly like hoodies and trainers. And most people don't even bother going to the office anymore. So that bit changed a lot. But the research process has obviously evolved. And I think one of the things is the bar has become higher. And I think the bar is likely to get higher, continuously to get higher. I must admit, when I started my career, I was a bit of a cynic. When it came to investment strategies or beating the market full stop. I had in my head that the market price encapsulated everything, more or less. And we'd do some work and we'd come up with a strategy. And it looked like it would win. It would beat the market. And I was thinking to myself, this is never going to last. So I always had that cynicism in my head. And I think I still do. But the fact that I still have a career and I'm still here must mean that something works with these strategies. But in terms of change of approach. For sure, as I said, the bar's got higher. Inefficiencies in markets get exploited. So when I started, I was working on a stat arb system in equities. And it was compared to today, very, very basic. Looked at reversion among pairs, neutralized the various factors. And it produced these lovely returns. But you could just see it decaying through time. And in order to keep up the edge, you needed to invest more data for better execution. You sued. You sued. And that was obvious then. And it's still the case now. And I think the net impact of all of that is it really affects the way you think about research. And the way you think about managing investment strategies. Back then, you could run a strategy and it would still work for years and years. You didn't really need to do very much. These days, that shelf life's a bit shorter. And therefore, the value of the ongoing research process is more important. So I think that. It's an evolution. More data, more processing power, more signals, higher inefficiencies being exploited, higher bar. All of that is pointing in one direction, which means you just need to work harder to stand still effectively.
